This is Lou Grivetti... I have logged-down and read all of our mutual
e-mails and wish first to offer my compliments for the diversity of
opinion, and the basic civility that we have shared this first week.
The first point I would like to make is not mine, but comes from Arthur
Varanelli -- who posted it to me back in December. I had asked for comments
from veterans and others regarding the course I had planned to teach at UC
Davis, and specifically asked why the Vietnamese-American War continued to
haunt Americans... Here is some of what Arthur said and I reproduce it here because
of its value to me and value for our dialogue:
<p>
 The forces of politics shaped the events that influenced the emotional
outcomes of the war. The politics are well known, as is the finger-pointing
and blame-placing that continues to this day. Politically, it seems
seems to be a game of musical chairs. Politically, the presidents,
Congresses, businesses, and the military played roles that were and
continue to be controversial.
<p>
It is true we can trace the origins of the Vietnam War through the history
of Vietnam.  I am sure careful historians can thread back to pre-World War II events
and attitudes which explain the causes of the war.
<p>
I feel to stop at this point, however, to miss the boat. I feel we need
to also examine American history to better appreciate the "cultural
psychology" at work behind the scenes. Some have suggested to me the Civil
War as a model.  I feel we need to go back further to the Revolutionary War
for more of the truth. I am not an historian, but I have an intuitive idea
that the emotions and politics at the time the American people invented
"revolutionary" warfare tactics and politics against the British Empire
leads us to a point where we can honestly consider that the reason why the
Vietnam War continues to haunt Americans is that we were at many levels
fighting ourselves, as we continue to do to this day.
<p>
The physical aspect of the Vietnam War ended over twenty years ago. We now need
to actively put to rest the "unburied."
<p>
