Though much still troubles me about the war and its aftermath, two books I've read in the past few years give a little more specificity.  I found both of them to be
very rich, so I'll just say one thing about each of them.
<p>
The first is WARRIOR DREAMS: VIOLENCE AND MANHOOD IN POST-VIETNAM AMERICA, by James William Gibson (who also wrote THE PERFECT WAR, a
remarkable book about the war itself).  Gibson traces what turns out to
be the prehistory of the militia movement from its origins in the
breakdown of core elements of white American male mythology.  Vietnam
was at the heart of it, but there were other causes as well.   A key
distinction he points out is that between earlier heroes, who fought in
order to restore a just moral order, and the "heroes" who've come out of
Vietnam, for whom war is endless, and its own justification.
<p>
The second is ECHOES OF COMBAT: THE VIETNAM WAR IN AMERICAN MEMORY, by Fred Turner.  Turner examines the process of remembering trauma, both at
an individual and a national level.  Reflecting back and forth between the two levels he is able to use them to illuminate one another.  It seems obvious to me that so long as we continue with certain kinds of denial we will never be at rest, we will never be able
to make our peace.  Considering that we have yet to make our peace with
the Civil War, the prospects do not look good.
<p>
