We have become a nation of special interests.  Instead of trying to
find areas of agreement (which this forum attempted, with some success),
groups in the US now are actively looking toward disagreement, toward how
we differ instead of how we are similar.  This is, I feel, another lesson
from the Vietnam era.  Special interests have power in our
society--voting power.  And the threat to use it can result in policy
change, in congressional action, and in the swaying of public opinion.
This has led to the present shrillness that I hear from the right side
of the political spectrum.
<p>
On the other side, we in the Pacific Northwest have undergone over a decade of turmoil
concerning the fight between environmentalists and the forest products
industry.  The same techniques used in the demonstrations against the
Vietnam War were and continue to be used in the demonstrations against
cutting old-growth forests.  And yes, there has been violence involved: a
forest service officer was killed in San Francisco recently by a letter
bomb, and a ranger station near Detroit, Oregon, was set on fire and
destroyed.  The latter resembles closely the tactics the "peace" movement used
against the ROTC at the University of Oregon in the 1960 (I believe), when
its offices were burned.  I'm not saying there is a direct connection, but that the
tactics are very similar.
<p>
