One of the elements of the aftermath of the war has been a thriving 
mythology about things that supposedly happened there. My least favorite, and the most persistent and maddening, is the myth of 
the living POWs, trotted out just yesterday in a particularly bizarre 
format on the TV show "The X-Files". Not only has the myth been thoroughly 
debunked by scholars, but also by the Reagan Administration (!) which 
released a report in its last days in office stating that the probability 
of living POWs in Southeast Asia was in the vicinity of 0. Interestingly, 
that story was completely buried in media reports, and the Bush 
administration acted as if such a report had never been released...
<p>
But we need to seriously examine much of this mythology, ask ourselves 
where it comes from, and why we seem to need to believe it, or at least 
propagate it, even if we have doubts.
<p>
