There is American pain regarding those missing in action (MIA) from the
Vietnamese-American War. The number of MIAs, however, is disproportionate:
c. 2,500 on the American side -- compared to c. 600,000 on the Vietnamese
side (both former North and South Vietnamese). Most of the cemeteries I
visited while driving south on Highway 1 from HaNoi to SaiGon do not
contain actual graves; they commemorate the men and women who never
returned to their villages--hundreds of thousands of them. The pain remains in all families who do not know the ultimate resting place of their loved ones--Americans as well as Vietnamese.
