The lessons of the war for the US? The "lessons" have been learned by
the aggressive, neo-colonialist elements in government, and the
military/industrial complex, not by the left or the opposition. What I mean
by that is, look at the conduct of the Gulf War. Lessons "learned" in the
war in Vietnam and applied to the Gulf War: 
<p>
1. Censor the news. 
<p>
2. Pick a weak opponent and pulverize them, but don't let the U.S. public see how
many civilians have been killed. 
<p>
3. Present the war in the media in terms of the neat high-tech offensive weaponry the U.S. has to deploy, not in terms of individual, suffering U.S. soldiers. 
<p>
4. Win fast and get out. 
<p>
5. Orchestrate all kinds of homecoming ceremonies for the triumphant US
troops, but don't help them out with their real needs (e.g.,Gulf War Syndrome).
<p>
6. Be sure to pick an enemy who can be presented as so alien as to be very
easily dehumanized, so nobody will care if 200,000 of them get slaughtered.
(E.g., don't go kill Serbians, because they're, after all, white, and you'd
be killing them in defense of people who are white, but Muslim... On the
other hand, "raghead/camel jockey/sand niggers" are in another category.
