All wars are lessons in extremes;  they bring out the best and worst of human behavior. The Vietnam War was no exception.  It brought out the
best in our society when we rediscovered the ability to challenge our
elected government's decisions in lawful ways and began a continuing
metamorphosis in the way we look at the affairs of others and our role
in those affairs.  It brought out the worst in our society because there
was never any closure to the war. The Vietnam War was born and fought in
the confusion of no clear national purpose. Long after the last shots of
combat were fired, we still fight the war amongst ourselves in an
attempt to find the answers to the questions of our involvement, what we
did, and what we really accomplished. Who won the Vietnam War? No one,
not yet.  
<p>
Often it is better to allow disagreements between people to be resolved
amongst themselves, regardless of how we perceive the brutality of the
conflict or how we are told about it.  The historical reasons for the
conflict may be such that nothing short of eradicating both sides will
bring the conflict to an end.  We must learn to discriminate between what
we are told we should do for cloudy political reasons and for reasons of
clear and present danger to ourselves or our way of life. All war has a
selfish content. We must make informed decisions on our purpose before
we commit our resources of people in acts of intervention. In our own
history, our Civil and Revolutionary Wars bring us questions to be
answered in these considerations. We must look into ourselves as well to
attempt to avoid another conflict like theVietnam War. 
<p>
